     8‚Üí
     9‚ÜíThis library provides [`anyhow::Error`][Error], a trait object based error type
    10‚Üífor easy idiomatic error handling in Rust applications.
    11‚Üí
    12‚Üí[Error]: https://docs.rs/anyhow/1.0/anyhow/struct.Error.html
    13‚Üí
    14‚Üí```toml
    15‚Üí[dependencies]
    16‚Üíanyhow = "1.0"
    17‚Üí```
    18‚Üí
    19‚Üí<br>
    20‚Üí
    21‚Üí## Details
    23‚Üí- Use `Result<T, anyhow::Error>`, or equivalently `anyhow::Result<T>`, as the
    24‚Üí  return type of any fallible function.
    25‚Üí
    26‚Üí  Within the function, use `?` to easily propagate any error that implements the
    27‚Üí  [`std::error::Error`] trait.
    28‚Üí
    29‚Üí  ```rust
    30‚Üí  use anyhow::Result;
    31‚Üí
    32‚Üí  fn get_cluster_info() -> Result<ClusterMap> {
    33‚Üí      let config = std::fs::read_to_string("cluster.json")?;
    34‚Üí      let map: ClusterMap = serde_json::from_str(&config)?;
    35‚Üí      Ok(map)
    36‚Üí  }
    37‚Üí  ```
    38‚Üí
    39‚Üí  [`std::error::Error`]: https://doc.rust-lang.org/std/error/trait.Error.html
    40‚Üí
    41‚Üí- Attach context to help the person troubleshooting the error understand where
    42‚Üí  things went wrong. A low-level error like "No such file or directory" can be
    43‚Üí  annoying to debug without more context about what higher level step the
    44‚Üí  application was in the middle of.
    45‚Üí
    46‚Üí  ```rust
    47‚Üí  use anyhow::{Context, Result};
    48‚Üí
    49‚Üí  fn main() -> Result<()> {
    50‚Üí      ...
    51‚Üí      it.detach().context("Failed to detach the important thing")?;
    52‚Üí
    53‚Üí      let content = std::fs::read(path)
    54‚Üí          .with_context(|| format!("Failed to read instrs from {}", path))?;
    55‚Üí      ...
    56‚Üí  }
    57‚Üí  ```
    58‚Üí
    59‚Üí  ```console
    60‚Üí  Error: Failed to read instrs from ./path/to/instrs.json
    61‚Üí
    62‚Üí  Caused by:
    63‚Üí      No such file or directory (os error 2)
    64‚Üí  ```
    65‚Üí
    66‚Üí- Downcasting is supported and can be by value, by shared reference, or by
    67‚Üí  mutable reference as needed.
    68‚Üí
    69‚Üí  ```rust
    70‚Üí  // If the error was caused by redaction, then return a
    71‚Üí  // tombstone instead of the content.
    72‚Üí  match root_cause.downcast_ref::<DataStoreError>() {
    73‚Üí      Some(DataStoreError::Censored(_)) => Ok(Poll::Ready(REDACTED_CONTENT)),
    74‚Üí      None => Err(error),
    75‚Üí  }
    76‚Üí  ```
    77‚Üí
      ‚Üí‚Ä¶
   126‚Üí## No-std support
   128‚ÜíIn no_std mode, almost all of the same API is available and works the same way.
   129‚ÜíTo depend on Anyhow in no_std mode, disable our default enabled "std" feature in
   130‚ÜíCargo.toml. A global allocator is required.
   131‚Üí
   132‚Üí```toml
   133‚Üí[dependencies]
   134‚Üíanyhow = { version = "1.0", default-features = false }
   135‚Üí```
   136‚Üí
   137‚ÜíWith versions of Rust older than 1.81, no_std mode may require an additional
   138‚Üí`.map_err(Error::msg)` when working with a non-Anyhow error type inside a
   139‚Üífunction that returns Anyhow's error type, as the trait that `?`-based error
   140‚Üíconversions are defined by is only available in std in those old versions.
   141‚Üí
   142‚Üí<br>
   143‚Üí
   144‚Üí## Comparison to failure
   146‚ÜíThe `anyhow::Error` type works something like `failure::Error`, but unlike
   147‚Üífailure ours is built around the standard library's `std::error::Error` trait
   148‚Üírather than a separate trait `failure::Fail`. The standard library has adopted
   149‚Üíthe necessary improvements for this to be possible as part of [RFC 2504].
   150‚Üí
   151‚Üí[RFC 2504]: https://github.com/rust-lang/rfcs/blob/master/text/2504-fix-error.md
   152‚Üí
   153‚Üí<br>
   154‚Üí
   155‚Üí## Comparison to thiserror
   157‚ÜíUse Anyhow if you don't care what error type your functions return, you just
   158‚Üíwant it to be easy. This is common in application code. Use [thiserror] if you
   159‚Üíare a library that wants to design your own dedicated error type(s) so that on
   160‚Üífailures the caller gets exactly the information that you choose.
   161‚Üí
   162‚Üí[thiserror]: https://github.com/dtolnay/thiserror
   163‚Üí
   164‚Üí<br>
   165‚Üí
